<subSubSection id="69AE97B7E450FFDBFF0732025E88FE94" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="210BC43CE450FFDBFF0732025E88FE94" blockId="10.[151,1436,151,357]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">
<emphasis id="13C0182EE450FFDBFF0732025F04FEB0" bold="true" box="[199,334,295,321]" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">Etymology.</emphasis>
This specific epithet is derived from the Latin 
<taxonomicName id="E6B4BFBFE450FFDBFC9C32025D9BFEB0" authorityName="Wang &amp; Wang &amp; Guan" authorityYear="2021" box="[860,977,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Heliodinidae" genus="Stathmopoda" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="461" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pyriformis">
<emphasis id="13C0182EE450FFDBFC9C32025D9BFEB0" box="[860,977,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="461">pyriformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, referring to the shape of the corpus bursae.
</paragraph>
